<body>
    <h1>Getting Started with Claude Code, GitHub, and Vercel: A Beginner&#3=
9;s Guide to AI Coding Workflow</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner's=
GuidetoAICodingWorkflow-ABeginner'sGuide=E2=80=94GitHub-ConnectedDesktopWor=
kflow">A Beginner's Guide =E2=80=94 GitHub-Connected Desktop Workflow</h3>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-=E2=9A=A0=EF=B8=8FBeforeYouStart:Security&amp;DataGuideline=
s">=E2=9A=A0=EF=B8=8F Before You Start: Security &amp; Data Guidelines</h2>
<p><strong>Please read this section before setting anything up.</strong> Th=
is guide is intended for personal learning and abstract experimentation =E2=
=80=94 not for building tools that interact with Mews systems, data, or int=
ernal workflows. The points below are not bureaucratic caution; they reflec=
t real incidents that have already happened and required security engineeri=
ng intervention.</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Whatbelongshere=E2=80=94andwhatdoesn't">What belongs here =
=E2=80=94 and what doesn't</h3>
<p>This workflow is appropriate for <strong>abstract, personal projects</st=
rong> =E2=80=94 things like a portfolio site, a side project, a learning ex=
ercise, or a proof-of-concept that has no connection to Mews systems, data,=
 or business processes.</p>
<p>It is <strong>not</strong> appropriate for:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Projects that interact with any Mews internal systems, APIs, or data (re=
servations, billing, customer data, operational workflows, etc.)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Workarounds for features that an internal platform doesn't currently sup=
port =E2=80=94 if a team has said no or doesn't have capacity to prioritise=
 something, building a "vibecoded" alternative is not the right path. These=
 solutions frequently don't meet the security or quality standards of the p=
latforms they're replacing, and often teams have invested time only to find=
 out a proper solution already exists or a different person could have redi=
rected them. If you're hitting a blocker like this, escalate or ask in the =
relevant Slack channels first.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Anything customer-facing or that could give a competitor or threat actor=
 insight into how Mews operates</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-KeepMewsdatainsideMewsinfrastructure">Keep Mews data inside=
 Mews infrastructure</h3>
<p><strong>No company data or workflows that touch internal Mews systems sh=
ould ever leave Mews infrastructure.</strong> This means:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Don't publish projects on free Vercel accounts (or any external hosting)=
 if they involve Mews data or interact with internal workflows</p></li>
<li>
<p>Don't connect Claude Code or any external AI tool to Mews systems withou=
t first checking with the relevant domain owners and security engineering</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>If you're unsure whether something counts as "Mews data", assume it does=
 and ask first</p></li>
</ul>
<p>If you need to build something that genuinely requires Mews data or syst=
em access, speak to the domain owners first =E2=80=94 they can tell you whe=
ther the tooling already exists, whether there's a safer way to do it, or w=
hether it's something the platform team is already working on.</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Ifyouneedtoexperiment=E2=80=94doitsafely">If you need to ex=
periment =E2=80=94 do it safely</h3>
<p>If you're using this workflow for legitimate personal or abstract experi=
mentation, here's what to watch for:</p>
<p><strong>Keep your repository private.</strong> There is almost never a r=
eason to make a repository public. A public repo means anyone on the intern=
et can see your code, your commit history, and =E2=80=94 critically =E2=80=
=94 any secrets you accidentally include. Default to private.</p>
<p><strong>Never commit secrets, API keys, or credentials to a repository =
=E2=80=94 public or private.</strong> This is the most common way keys get =
leaked. Incidents of this kind have already occurred at Mews and required s=
ecurity engineering to contain. Specifically:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Do not hardcode API keys, tokens, passwords, or connection strings direc=
tly in your code</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use environment variables (<code>.env</code> files) for any credentials =
=E2=80=94 and add <code>.env</code> to your <code>.gitignore</code> so it's=
 never committed</p></li>
<li>
<p>If you accidentally commit a secret, assume it is compromised immediatel=
y =E2=80=94 rotate the key and notify security engineering</p></li>
<li>
<p>Check your commits carefully before pushing, especially if your repo is =
or ever was public</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Ask before connecting to anything Mews-related.</strong> If you =
find yourself thinking "I'll just wire this up to the Mews API to test it" =
=E2=80=94 stop and ask the domain owners first. They can confirm whether th=
is is safe, already possible through existing tooling, or something that sh=
ould go through a proper process.</p>
<p><strong>Be realistic about support.</strong> Vibes-coded solutions are h=
ard to maintain, debug, and hand off. Security and platform teams are not a=
lways able to support custom-built tools that bypass standard systems =E2=
=80=94 and the time cost of those support requests is unpredictable. Build =
things that are genuinely useful and scoped, not just because it's now tech=
nically easy to do so.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-WhatAreWeSettingUp=E2=80=94AndWhy?">What Are We Setting Up =
=E2=80=94 And Why?</h2>
<p>Before touching any tools, here's the big picture of what you're buildin=
g and why each piece matters.</p>
<p><strong>Claude Code</strong> is your AI coding assistant. You describe w=
hat you want in plain English and it reads your files, writes code, and fix=
es errors =E2=80=94 autonomously. The Desktop app gives you all of this thr=
ough a visual, point-and-click interface.[1]</p>
<p><strong>GitHub</strong> is where your code lives online. It's a cloud pl=
atform that tracks every change you make to your code over time, lets you r=
oll back mistakes, and makes it easy to deploy your project. Think of it li=
ke Google Drive, but designed for code =E2=80=94 with a full history of eve=
ry edit ever made.[2][3]</p>
<p><strong>Vercel</strong> takes your code from GitHub and publishes it liv=
e on the internet automatically. Every time you push a change to GitHub, Ve=
rcel rebuilds and redeploys your site within minutes =E2=80=94 no server ma=
nagement required. It's free to start.[4]</p>
<p><strong>The workflow in one sentence:</strong> You use Claude Code Deskt=
op (connected to your GitHub repo) to write and edit code =E2=86=92 changes=
 are committed directly to GitHub =E2=86=92 Vercel picks them up automatica=
lly and goes live.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step1:CreateaGitHubAccount">Step 1: Create a GitHub Account=
</h2>
<p>GitHub is the foundation of this entire setup =E2=80=94 start here.</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-SignupwithGoogle">Sign up with Google</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Go to <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://github.com" rel=3D"nofo=
llow"><strong>github.com</strong></a></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Sign up</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Continue with Google</strong> to use your Gmail =E2=80=94 =
no separate password needed[5]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Choose a username (keep it professional =E2=80=94 you'll use it permanen=
tly)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Verify your email address when prompted[5]</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Createyourfirstrepository">Create your first repository</h3=
>
<p>A repository ("repo") is a folder for your project that GitHub tracks =
=E2=80=94 including the full history of every change ever made.[6]</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>From your GitHub dashboard, click the green <strong>New</strong> or <str=
ong>Create repository</strong> button[7]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Give it a name (e.g., <code>my-first-project</code>) =E2=80=94 no spaces=
, use hyphens</p></li>
<li>
<p>Add a short description</p></li>
<li>
<p>Set it to <strong>Private</strong> =E2=80=94 keep your code private unle=
ss you have a specific reason to make it public (see the security guideline=
s above)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Tick <strong>Add a README file</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Create repository</strong>[8]</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Your repository is now live at <code>github.com/your-username/my-first-p=
roject</code>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step2:InstallClaudeCodeDesktop">Step 2: Install Claude Code=
 Desktop</h2>
<p>The Desktop app includes everything built in =E2=80=94 no terminal, no N=
ode.js, no command-line setup needed.[1]</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Requirements">Requirements</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>Claude Pro, Max, Team, or Enterprise subscription</strong> =E2=
=80=94 the free tier does not include Claude Code[1]</p></li>
<li>
<p>macOS or Windows (Linux is not currently supported)[1]</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Downloadandinstall">Download and install</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Go to <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://claude.ai" rel=3D"nofol=
low"><strong>claude.ai</strong></a> and download the desktop app for your p=
latform</p></li>
<li>
<p>Install it like any normal app =E2=80=94 open the <code>.dmg</code> on M=
ac or run the <code>.exe</code> on Windows</p></li>
<li>
<p>Launch Claude and sign in with your Anthropic account</p></li>
<li>
<p>Click the <strong>Code</strong> tab at the top of the app[1]</p></li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>If clicking Code prompts an upgrade, you need a paid subscription first.=
 If you see a 403 error, sign out and sign back in =E2=80=94 that fixes it =
in most cases.[9]</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step3:ConnectClaudeCodetoYourGitHubRepository">Step 3: Conn=
ect Claude Code to Your GitHub Repository</h2>
<p>Instead of selecting a local folder, you'll connect Claude directly to y=
our GitHub repo so it works in the cloud =E2=80=94 no files on your compute=
r needed.</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-InstalltheGitHubApp">Install the GitHub App</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>In the Code tab, click the <strong>+</strong> button next to the prompt =
box</p></li>
<li>
<p>Select <strong>Connectors</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>GitHub</strong>[9]<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Install GitHub App</strong> =E2=80=94 this takes you to Gi=
tHub to authorise Claude[10]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Choose your account and select either <strong>All repositories</strong> =
or specific ones[10]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Install</strong> =E2=80=94 you'll be redirected back to Cl=
aude</p></li>
</ol>
<p>This is a one-time setup. Once done, Claude can access any repo you've g=
ranted it permission to.[11]</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Addarepositorytoyoursession">Add a repository to your sessi=
on</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>In the environment dropdown, select <strong>Remote</strong>[1]</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Remote sessions run on Anthropic's cloud infrastructure and keep running=
 even if you close the app[9]</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Click the <strong>+</strong> button next to the repo selector and add yo=
ur GitHub repository[9]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Select the repo you created in Step 1</p></li>
<li>
<p>Choose a model (Sonnet is a good default)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Type your first task and press <strong>Enter</strong></p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step4:InstalltheSuperpowersPlugin">Step 4: Install the Supe=
rpowers Plugin</h2>
<p>Out of the box, Claude Code is already powerful =E2=80=94 but the <stron=
g>Superpowers plugin</strong> takes it further. It's the most popular plugi=
n in the Claude Code ecosystem with 43,000+ GitHub stars and is now officia=
lly listed in the Anthropic plugin marketplace.[12]</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-WhatdoesSuperpowersactuallydo?">What does Superpowers actua=
lly do?</h3>
<p>Without Superpowers, Claude can jump straight into writing code =E2=80=
=94 which sometimes means rushing in before fully understanding the problem=
. Superpowers adds a structured three-step workflow that mirrors how senior=
 developers actually work:[13]</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Brainstorm</strong> =E2=80=94 Claude asks clarifying questions a=
nd refines your idea before touching any code</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Write Plan</strong> =E2=80=94 Claude produces a detailed impleme=
ntation plan (phases, files to change, acceptance criteria) for you to revi=
ew and approve</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Execute Plan</strong> =E2=80=94 Claude implements the plan in st=
ructured batches with review checkpoints, not all at once</p></li>
</ol>
<p>This means fewer dead ends, less "it seemed to work then broke everythin=
g" situations, and more predictable results =E2=80=94 especially on complex=
 or existing projects.[12]</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-InstallviathePluginMarketplace">Install via the Plugin Mark=
etplace</h3>
<p>Installing Superpowers requires no terminal. Do it entirely inside the C=
laude Code Desktop app:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>In the Code tab, click the <strong>+</strong> button next to the prompt =
box</p></li>
<li>
<p>Select <strong>Plugins</strong>[9]</p></li>
<li>
<p>In the plugins panel, click <strong>Discover</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Search for <strong>superpowers</strong> and select it from the results[1=
2]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Choose whether to install for yourself only or all projects</p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Install</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click the <strong>+</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>Plugins</strong> panel ag=
ain =E2=80=94 under <strong>Installed</strong> you should see Superpowers w=
ith its three commands listed: <code>execute-plan</code>, <code>write-plan<=
/code>, and <code>brainstorm</code>[12]</p></li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Tip:</strong> To update Superpowers in future, go back to <stron=
g>Plugins</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>Installed</strong> =E2=86=92 click <st=
rong>Update</strong>. The plugin team releases improvements regularly.[12]<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-HowtouseSuperpowers">How to use Superpowers</h3>
<p>Every time you start a new session, type <strong>"using superpowers"</st=
rong> at the start of your first message =E2=80=94 this reminds Claude that=
 the plugin is active and to follow its structured workflow.[12]</p>
<p>Then use the slash commands:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Command</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>When to use it</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>/superpowers:brainstorm</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Starting a new feature =E2=80=94 refine your idea before any code is wri=
tten[13]</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>/superpowers:write-plan</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>After brainstorming =E2=80=94 generates a phased implementation plan to =
review[13]</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>/superpowers:execute-plan</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>After approving the plan =E2=80=94 Claude builds in structured batches w=
ith checkpoints[13]</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Example flow:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Type: <em>"using superpowers"</em></p></li>
<li>
<p><code>/superpowers:brainstorm</code> =E2=86=92 describe your idea, answe=
r Claude's questions</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>/superpowers:write-plan</code> =E2=86=92 review the plan Claude cr=
eates, ask for changes</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>/superpowers:execute-plan</code> =E2=86=92 Claude builds it phase =
by phase</p></li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step5:BuildSomething">Step 5: Build Something</h2>
<p>With your GitHub repo connected and Superpowers installed, you're ready =
to build. Run <code>/superpowers:brainstorm</code> and describe what you wa=
nt in plain English:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>"I want to build a simple personal portfolio website with an about s=
ection, a projects section, and a contact form."</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Claude will ask clarifying questions, generate a plan, and then build it=
 phase by phase =E2=80=94 all on its own branch in your GitHub repo. Claude=
 does <strong>not</strong> edit your <code>main</code> branch directly, kee=
ping your main code safe until you're ready to merge.[10][9]</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Reviewandapprovechanges">Review and approve changes</h3>
<p>When Claude finishes a task, a diff stats indicator appears (e.g., <code=
>+12 -1</code>). Click it to open the <strong>diff view</strong>:[9]</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>See exactly what changed, file by file (green =3D added, red =3D removed=
)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Leave inline comments on specific lines =E2=80=94 Claude reads them and =
revises[9]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Review code</strong> to have Claude audit its own changes =
before you commit[9]</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step6:MergeChangestoGitHub">Step 6: Merge Changes to GitHub=
</h2>
<p>Once you're happy with Claude's work, merge it into your <code>main</cod=
e> branch.</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-CreateaPullRequest">Create a Pull Request</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>In the Claude Code session toolbar, click <strong>Create PR</strong>[10]=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>Give it a title and description =E2=80=94 Claude can write this for you<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Create</strong> =E2=80=94 this opens a Pull Request on you=
r GitHub repo</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-MergethePullRequest">Merge the Pull Request</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Go to <code>github.com/your-username/my-first-project</code></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click the banner for the new Pull Request</p></li>
<li>
<p>Review the changes one final time</p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Merge pull request</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>Confirm merg=
e</strong>[10]</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Your <code>main</code> branch now has the latest code. This is what Verc=
el will deploy.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Step7:DeploywithVercel">Step 7: Deploy with Vercel</h2>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Important:</strong> Only use Vercel to deploy personal, abstract=
 projects with no connection to Mews data or internal systems. Do not deplo=
y anything on a free Vercel account (or any external hosting) that touches =
Mews workflows, APIs, or customer data. See the security guidelines at the =
top of this page.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Vercel connects to your GitHub <code>main</code> branch and publishes yo=
ur site live =E2=80=94 automatically on every merge.</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-CreateaVercelaccount">Create a Vercel account</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Go to <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://vercel.com" rel=3D"nofo=
llow"><strong>vercel.com</strong></a></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Sign Up</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>Continue with GitHub</s=
trong>[14]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Authorise Vercel to access your GitHub account</p></li>
</ol>
<p>The <strong>Hobby plan is completely free</strong> to get started.[14]</=
p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Deployyourproject">Deploy your project</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>From your Vercel dashboard, click <strong>Add New =E2=86=92 Project</str=
ong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Import</strong> next to your GitHub repo[15]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Vercel auto-detects your project type and sets up build settings automat=
ically[16]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Click <strong>Deploy</strong></p></li>
</ol>
<p>Within 1=E2=80=932 minutes, Vercel gives you a live URL: <code>your-proj=
ect-name.vercel.app</code>.[17]</p>
<h3 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-Howautomaticdeployswork">How automatic deploys work</h3>
<p>Every time a Pull Request is merged into <code>main</code>, <strong>Verc=
el automatically rebuilds and redeploys your site</strong>. Your complete o=
ngoing workflow is:[17]</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Open Claude Code Desktop =E2=86=92 connect to your GitHub repo =E2=86=92=
 describe the change</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use Superpowers for structured planning =E2=86=92 review Claude's diff =
=E2=86=92 Create PR =E2=86=92 Merge to main</p></li>
<li>
<p>Vercel auto-deploys =E2=80=94 live within ~60 seconds</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-TheFullWorkflowataGlance">The Full Workflow at a Glance</h2=
>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Claude =
Code Desktop (GitHub Remote session)
              =E2=86=93
  /superpowers:brainstorm =E2=86=92 refine your idea
              =E2=86=93
  /superpowers:write-plan =E2=86=92 review the plan
              =E2=86=93
  /superpowers:execute-plan =E2=86=92 Claude builds on its own branch
              =E2=86=93
  Review diff =E2=86=92 Create Pull Request =E2=86=92 Merge to main
              =E2=86=93
  Vercel detects merge =E2=86=92 auto-rebuilds =E2=86=92 goes live
              =E2=86=93
  Your site at yourproject.vercel.app</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-KeyConceptsGlossary">Key Concepts Glossary</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Term</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>What it means</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Repository (repo)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Your project folder on GitHub, with full change history[6]</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Branch</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A separate copy of your code Claude works on, without touching main[10]<=
/p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Commit</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A saved snapshot of changes, with a message describing what changed[2]</=
p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Pull Request (PR)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A request to merge Claude's branch into your main branch[10]</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Merge</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Combining Claude's branch into main =E2=80=94 this triggers a Vercel dep=
loy</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Remote session</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Claude runs in the cloud, connected to GitHub directly, not your machine=
[9]</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Diff</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A visual comparison showing exactly what code was added or removed[9]</p=
></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Plugin / Skill</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A reusable package that adds commands and workflows to Claude Code[9]</p=
></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"GettingStartedwithClaudeCode,GitHub,andVercel:ABeginner'sGuidetoA=
ICodingWorkflow-TroubleshootingCommonIssues">Troubleshooting Common Issues<=
/h2>
<p><strong>Clicking Code prompts an upgrade</strong><br>
You need a paid Claude subscription (Pro at $20/month minimum).[1]</p>
<p><strong>GitHub connector not showing your repo</strong><br>
Go to <code>github.com/settings/installations</code> and grant Claude acces=
s to the specific repository.[11]</p>
<p><strong>Superpowers commands not appearing after install</strong><br>
Go to <strong>+</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>Plugins</strong> =E2=86=92 <stro=
ng>Installed</strong> and confirm Superpowers is listed. If not, try instal=
ling again or restart the app.[12]</p>
<p><strong>403 error in the Code tab</strong><br>
Sign out of the app completely, sign back in, and restart.[9]</p>
<p><strong>Vercel deployment fails after merge</strong><br>
Check the build logs in your Vercel dashboard =E2=80=94 it shows exactly wh=
at went wrong. Most common cause: a missing file or broken import in your c=
ode.</p>
<p><strong>Changes not showing on Vercel</strong><br>
Confirm the PR was merged into the <code>main</code> branch specifically =
=E2=80=94 Vercel watches <code>main</code> by default.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
